# DTO Boundary

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

This rule has no exceptions. There is no scenario - not a "simple"
entity, not a one-off display, not urgency - that permits passing a
domain entity across the IPC boundary to the renderer.

Prohibited judgement calls:
- "This entity only has two fields, a DTO is overkill." - No. Create the DTO.
- "I'll pass the entity directly for now and add the DTO later." - No. The DTO is required before the task is done.
- "The renderer only reads one field, it doesn't need the full DTO." - No. All data crossing the IPC boundary goes through a DTO.
- "I'll add the new field to the entity and read it in the renderer directly." - No. Add it to the DTO.

---

Domain entities must never cross the IPC boundary from the main process
to the renderer. Always convert to a Data Transfer Object (DTO) first.

## Why this matters for Electron specifically

Domain entities may be class instances with methods, private fields, and
circular references. Electron's IPC serializes data using the structured
clone algorithm, which cannot serialize class instances, functions, or
circular references. Sending a domain entity across IPC will either throw
a runtime error or silently strip methods and private state.

DTOs are plain TypeScript interfaces with only serializable data. They
always survive IPC serialization safely.

## Pattern

DTOs live in `src/shared/dtos/`. They are plain TypeScript interfaces
(not classes) so they are importable from both the main and renderer process.

```typescript
// src/shared/dtos/subject-dto.ts
export interface SubjectDTO {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  type: 'Individual' | 'Organization';
  raceContext: string | null;
  status: 'Active' | 'Inactive' | 'Archived';
  notes: string | null;
  createdAt: string; // ISO 8601 string, not Date object
}
```

Conversion from domain entity to DTO happens in the infrastructure layer
or use case:

```typescript
// src/main/infrastructure/repositories/subject-repository.ts
function toSubjectDTO(row: SubjectRow): SubjectDTO {
  return {
    id: row.id,
    name: row.name,
    type: row.type,
    raceContext: row.race_context,
    status: row.status,
    notes: row.notes,
    createdAt: row.created_at,
  };
}
```

The IPC handler returns the DTO:

```typescript
ipcMain.handle('subjects:get', async (_event, id: string) => {
  try {
    const dto = await container.getSubjectUseCase().execute(id);
    return { ok: true, data: dto };
  } catch (error) {
    return { ok: false, error: 'Subject not found' };
  }
});
```

The renderer works with the plain DTO interface only:

```typescript
// src/renderer/components/SubjectCard.tsx
interface Props {
  subject: SubjectDTO; // imported from src/shared/dtos/subject-dto
}
```

## Date serialization

`Date` objects are not safely cloneable across IPC in all Electron
versions. Always serialize dates as ISO 8601 strings in DTOs
(`string` type, not `Date`). The renderer converts to a `Date` object
locally if needed for display formatting.

## Rules

- DTOs are plain interfaces, not classes. No methods, no inheritance.
- All dates in DTOs are ISO 8601 strings.
- DTOs live in `src/shared/dtos/`. They may be imported from any layer.
- Use cases return DTOs. IPC handlers pass them to the renderer as-is.
- If the renderer needs a new field, add it to the DTO in `src/shared/dtos/`.
  Do not reach into the domain entity from the renderer.

